1
00:01:30,980 --> 00:01:35,030
[The Lost National Treasure]

2
00:01:35,070 --> 00:01:37,810
[Episode 23]

3
00:01:48,920 --> 00:01:49,850
Fifty thousand.

4
00:01:58,120 --> 00:02:00,710
This antique-style thing is just a copy.

5
00:02:01,510 --> 00:02:02,520
I can pay for it,

6
00:02:03,070 --> 00:02:05,040
but I need to be fully convinced.

7
00:02:12,080 --> 00:02:12,710
Dude,

8
00:02:13,840 --> 00:02:15,040
I heard from my nephew

9
00:02:15,280 --> 00:02:16,810
that you're also an expert.

10
00:02:17,800 --> 00:02:19,190
I'd like to test you.

11
00:02:20,870 --> 00:02:21,840
There's both

12
00:02:22,910 --> 00:02:23,970
real and fake stuff

13
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:24,800
in this place.

14
00:02:25,310 --> 00:02:26,430
Can you tell?

15
00:02:35,360 --> 00:02:36,020
Be careful.

16
00:02:36,470 --> 00:02:37,200
Don't worry.

17
00:02:50,750 --> 00:02:52,190
This Lang kilin red vase—

18
00:02:52,960 --> 00:02:54,220
You could say it's real

19
00:02:54,310 --> 00:02:55,590
or fake.

20
00:02:57,190 --> 00:02:58,120
Tell me about it.

21
00:03:00,310 --> 00:03:04,170
During the Qing's Kangxi era,
many Xuande porcelains were imitated,

22
00:03:04,960 --> 00:03:06,380
but

23
00:03:07,120 --> 00:03:09,850
they failed to replicate
the Xuande red porcelain.

24
00:03:09,850 --> 00:03:11,980
Later, Lang Tingji from the Kangxi era

25
00:03:12,470 --> 00:03:14,400
successfully imitated the Lang kiln red,

26
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:16,560
which is as red as chicken blood,

27
00:03:17,079 --> 00:03:19,079
with ox-hair patterns in the glaze,

28
00:03:19,240 --> 00:03:20,310
an unglazed base,

29
00:03:20,910 --> 00:03:22,520
and white straw-wick edging.

30
00:03:22,520 --> 00:03:23,470
Call it real—

31
00:03:23,960 --> 00:03:25,760
it's real by today's standards.

32
00:03:26,360 --> 00:03:27,090
Call it fake—

33
00:03:27,870 --> 00:03:28,960
it's a copy

34
00:03:29,590 --> 00:03:30,750
in the Qing dynasty.

35
00:03:31,710 --> 00:03:33,030
You've got sharp eyes.

36
00:03:34,190 --> 00:03:34,720
However,

37
00:03:35,190 --> 00:03:36,280
even I was almost

38
00:03:36,840 --> 00:03:37,560
fooled

39
00:03:37,960 --> 00:03:39,190
by your vase.

40
00:03:44,590 --> 00:03:45,680
So you mean

41
00:03:46,120 --> 00:03:46,960
this

42
00:03:47,470 --> 00:03:48,520
is still a fake?

43
00:03:49,560 --> 00:03:50,750
Craft-wise,

44
00:03:51,030 --> 00:03:52,610
I can say it's flawless.

45
00:03:53,430 --> 00:03:54,400
Look at the base—

46
00:03:55,240 --> 00:03:56,800
the glaze stops cleanly,

47
00:03:57,079 --> 00:03:58,800
which takes real skill.

48
00:03:59,190 --> 00:04:01,230
The firing was spot-on.

49
00:04:01,560 --> 00:04:02,120
I dare say

50
00:04:02,430 --> 00:04:04,490
even a craftsman from Kangxi's time

51
00:04:04,750 --> 00:04:05,960
would be impressed.

52
00:04:06,680 --> 00:04:08,150
You're an expert indeed.

53
00:04:10,710 --> 00:04:11,750
So why

54
00:04:12,840 --> 00:04:13,520
do you

55
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:14,800
say it's fake?

56
00:04:16,120 --> 00:04:17,000
Visually,

57
00:04:17,600 --> 00:04:18,920
it fooled me too.

58
00:04:19,630 --> 00:04:20,690
But once I held it,

59
00:04:20,970 --> 00:04:22,430
I knew it was fake.

60
00:04:23,360 --> 00:04:25,830
A real Lang kilin red is

61
00:04:26,120 --> 00:04:27,190
evenly weighted.

62
00:04:27,720 --> 00:04:30,180
But this one's top-light and bottom-heavy.

63
00:04:30,510 --> 00:04:33,360
All the weight sits at the base.

64
00:04:36,120 --> 00:04:36,800
Dude,

65
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:39,600
at least ten experts

66
00:04:40,120 --> 00:04:41,560
have seen this vase.

67
00:04:42,240 --> 00:04:42,830
Not one

68
00:04:43,480 --> 00:04:44,680
dared say it was fake.

69
00:04:44,830 --> 00:04:46,430
Experts won't say it,

70
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:48,310
but what if we test it with machines?

71
00:04:48,310 --> 00:04:49,170
What machines?

72
00:04:49,430 --> 00:04:50,890
Aren't they man-made too?

73
00:04:51,720 --> 00:04:52,920
To tell you the truth,

74
00:04:53,560 --> 00:04:54,240
in our town,

75
00:04:55,040 --> 00:04:57,600
whether it's glaze from

76
00:04:57,920 --> 00:05:00,330
the Ming's Chenghua era or Qing's Kangxi,

77
00:05:00,360 --> 00:05:01,240
you can buy it,

78
00:05:01,800 --> 00:05:04,390
and take soil from ancient kiln sites

79
00:05:04,870 --> 00:05:05,880
to fire porcelain.

80
00:05:05,880 --> 00:05:09,260
Its composition will be
exactly like the originals.

81
00:05:11,600 --> 00:05:13,190
You're being so honest.

82
00:05:13,630 --> 00:05:15,430
Aren't you afraid I'll steal it?

83
00:05:15,920 --> 00:05:17,430
What I just told you

84
00:05:18,070 --> 00:05:20,600
took our ancestors
over 100 years to develop.

85
00:05:20,830 --> 00:05:21,870
You think you can steal that?

86
00:05:21,870 --> 00:05:23,600
Still fake in the end, isn't it?

87
00:05:24,040 --> 00:05:25,190
My brother was right.

88
00:05:25,190 --> 00:05:27,040
Your brother was right indeed,

89
00:05:28,190 --> 00:05:29,990
but he doesn't get the final say.

90
00:05:30,830 --> 00:05:31,750
No offense,

91
00:05:32,750 --> 00:05:33,610
but who are you?

92
00:05:34,120 --> 00:05:35,830
Can you override ten experts?

93
00:05:36,640 --> 00:05:37,390
Sir,

94
00:05:37,600 --> 00:05:39,390
seems I misjudged this time.

95
00:05:40,480 --> 00:05:43,010
I said I wanted to be
convinced before buying.

96
00:05:43,390 --> 00:05:44,480
And now I've seen

97
00:05:44,800 --> 00:05:46,000
your craftsmanship.

98
00:05:46,430 --> 00:05:47,870
I'll take the vase.

99
00:05:48,640 --> 00:05:49,840
You can't afford it.

100
00:06:00,870 --> 00:06:01,800
Not even close.

101
00:06:02,120 --> 00:06:04,120
You can sell it to a private museum.

102
00:06:04,390 --> 00:06:05,730
Why not me?

103
00:06:06,870 --> 00:06:07,680
Dude,

104
00:06:08,680 --> 00:06:10,880
you're quite the stickler, aren't you?

105
00:06:11,510 --> 00:06:13,310
If we're really getting into it,

106
00:06:13,560 --> 00:06:15,220
how could you tolerate fakes?

107
00:06:16,430 --> 00:06:18,030
Those who come to buy from me,

108
00:06:18,160 --> 00:06:19,430
some have poor judgment,

109
00:06:19,430 --> 00:06:21,630
some just turn a blind eye,

110
00:06:22,310 --> 00:06:25,560
but no one stares at
every flaw like you do.

111
00:06:28,390 --> 00:06:30,650
I've been in this trade for over 40 years.

112
00:06:31,120 --> 00:06:33,560
Faking pieces is the easy part.

113
00:06:34,190 --> 00:06:35,460
Reading people

114
00:06:35,920 --> 00:06:37,180
is one of my skills too.

115
00:06:38,070 --> 00:06:39,000
You're a master.

116
00:06:39,960 --> 00:06:41,290
I can't see through you.

117
00:06:42,360 --> 00:06:44,040
But this guy beside you?

118
00:06:44,040 --> 00:06:45,560
One look and I know

119
00:06:46,409 --> 00:06:47,650
he's a tomb raider.

120
00:06:52,390 --> 00:06:53,040
Sir,

121
00:06:53,440 --> 00:06:54,700
you've got sharp eyes.

122
00:06:55,680 --> 00:06:57,340
We only deal in real antiques,

123
00:06:57,430 --> 00:06:58,890
and you only deal in fakes.

124
00:06:58,950 --> 00:07:01,550
Normally, we don't
interfere with each other.

125
00:07:02,120 --> 00:07:05,020
But your business is getting too big—

126
00:07:05,190 --> 00:07:07,360
even my clients are buying your stuff.

127
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:09,480
I don't mean anything else.

128
00:07:09,480 --> 00:07:10,480
I'm just curious

129
00:07:10,680 --> 00:07:13,630
who on earth could fool them.

130
00:07:13,810 --> 00:07:14,220
Wrong.

131
00:07:15,440 --> 00:07:16,180
Not fooled.

132
00:07:16,870 --> 00:07:18,720
They bought it willingly.

133
00:07:20,430 --> 00:07:21,560
So what if it's fake?

134
00:07:22,190 --> 00:07:25,120
Even emperors Yongzheng
and Qianlong liked copies.

135
00:07:26,270 --> 00:07:28,200
There are so many antique dealers,

136
00:07:28,390 --> 00:07:30,480
but not enough real stuff to go around.

137
00:07:30,480 --> 00:07:32,190
Fakes fill the gaps.

138
00:07:33,390 --> 00:07:35,320
Private museums, auction houses—

139
00:07:36,190 --> 00:07:37,990
how would they survive without

140
00:07:38,480 --> 00:07:39,040
my fakes?

141
00:07:40,270 --> 00:07:42,330
Nine out of ten collectors buy fakes.

142
00:07:42,659 --> 00:07:44,560
Nine out of ten experts are dumb.

143
00:07:45,020 --> 00:07:47,280
The poor want to get rich overnight.

144
00:07:48,040 --> 00:07:50,370
The rich want to keep
or grow their wealth.

145
00:07:51,159 --> 00:07:52,750
As long as someone's buying,

146
00:07:52,750 --> 00:07:53,560
I could

147
00:07:53,940 --> 00:07:54,890
call it

148
00:07:55,510 --> 00:07:56,190
real or fake

149
00:07:56,800 --> 00:07:57,830
as I like.

150
00:08:01,560 --> 00:08:03,800
Sir, this trip wasn't in vain.

151
00:08:04,190 --> 00:08:05,250
I've learned a lot.

152
00:08:15,190 --> 00:08:17,120
The money isn't taken for nothing.

153
00:08:18,070 --> 00:08:20,000
Apart from this Lang kiln red vase,

154
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:22,400
pick anything else you like.

155
00:08:23,360 --> 00:08:25,020
I'll give you one more advice:

156
00:08:25,480 --> 00:08:27,010
Water too clear has no fish;

157
00:08:27,510 --> 00:08:29,840
People too discerning have no followers.

158
00:08:30,700 --> 00:08:31,750
In this circle,

159
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:35,049
how many truly deal in genuine artifacts?

160
00:08:39,440 --> 00:08:39,840
Guang,

161
00:08:41,480 --> 00:08:43,030
"Water too clear has no fish;

162
00:08:43,030 --> 00:08:44,410
People too discerning have no followers."

163
00:08:44,410 --> 00:08:45,740
You get what that means?

164
00:08:46,720 --> 00:08:49,200
Means clear water can't support fish.

165
00:08:49,720 --> 00:08:50,200
But

166
00:08:50,840 --> 00:08:53,000
what's that second part about?

167
00:08:53,240 --> 00:08:54,320
The second part means

168
00:08:54,320 --> 00:08:57,520
if a person sees too clearly,
they'll have no companions.

169
00:08:58,300 --> 00:08:59,470
I still don't understand

170
00:08:59,470 --> 00:09:00,730
what we went there for.

171
00:09:00,750 --> 00:09:02,150
We paid tens of thousands

172
00:09:02,480 --> 00:09:04,410
and came back with this fake plate.

173
00:09:04,440 --> 00:09:05,030
Why?

174
00:09:05,750 --> 00:09:06,390
The truth.

175
00:09:07,150 --> 00:09:07,750
The truth?

176
00:09:09,870 --> 00:09:11,320
You know how that fake plate

177
00:09:11,320 --> 00:09:13,030
ended up in the Mingde Museum?

178
00:09:14,750 --> 00:09:15,910
Xiao bought it,

179
00:09:16,480 --> 00:09:17,610
to fool Zhao Youlin.

180
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:20,720
You really think

181
00:09:20,720 --> 00:09:22,550
Zhao Youlin didn't know it was fake?

182
00:09:22,550 --> 00:09:23,480
Even if he knew it was fake,

183
00:09:23,480 --> 00:09:25,480
his friends didn't know what it was.

184
00:09:25,720 --> 00:09:26,960
Do you think his friends

185
00:09:26,960 --> 00:09:28,220
didn't know it's fake?

186
00:09:29,320 --> 00:09:31,720
You think they really care about antiques?

187
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:33,600
Then what do they care about?

188
00:09:33,750 --> 00:09:36,440
To them, authenticity doesn't matter.

189
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:38,870
Connections do.

190
00:09:39,480 --> 00:09:42,480
They don't play antiques.
They play people.

191
00:09:44,670 --> 00:09:46,200
In times without heroes,

192
00:09:47,150 --> 00:09:49,150
even scoundrels can become famous.

193
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:51,330
Those in high positions

194
00:09:51,750 --> 00:09:53,790
are full of opportunists.

195
00:09:55,630 --> 00:09:56,760
What does that mean?

196
00:09:58,600 --> 00:10:00,860
Not to know is not to know. That's wisdom.

197
00:10:01,390 --> 00:10:03,720
You're wiser than Zhao Youlin and his men.

198
00:10:04,870 --> 00:10:05,400
Let's go.

199
00:10:05,790 --> 00:10:06,450
From now on,

200
00:10:06,840 --> 00:10:08,370
we have a lot to do.

201
00:10:08,400 --> 00:10:08,750
Okay.

202
00:10:10,480 --> 00:10:11,720
Jianhui, you didn't take the plate.

203
00:10:11,720 --> 00:10:13,360
Just leave it there for use.

204
00:10:14,480 --> 00:10:15,440
You can keep it.

205
00:10:15,910 --> 00:10:16,930
Alright, thanks.

206
00:10:24,600 --> 00:10:25,120
Wen Wen.

207
00:10:27,150 --> 00:10:27,610
Wen Wen.

208
00:10:32,110 --> 00:10:32,720
I'm back.

209
00:10:33,240 --> 00:10:33,690
You're back.

210
00:10:33,690 --> 00:10:36,020
Wait, let me wash my hands. They're dirty.

211
00:10:42,440 --> 00:10:44,300
I forgot to change my shoes again.

212
00:11:00,910 --> 00:11:02,840
I must say, you're quite carefree.

213
00:11:02,910 --> 00:11:04,120
She's already 11 weeks pregnant.

214
00:11:04,120 --> 00:11:05,380
Why are you coming now?

215
00:11:06,960 --> 00:11:07,870
11 weeks?

216
00:11:09,080 --> 00:11:10,750
I'm sorry, doctor. I'm so sorry.

217
00:11:10,750 --> 00:11:12,360
I... I really was too careless.

218
00:11:12,360 --> 00:11:13,800
Why are you apologizing to me?

219
00:11:13,800 --> 00:11:15,730
You should apologize to your wife.

220
00:11:17,750 --> 00:11:18,360
I'm sorry.

221
00:11:20,660 --> 00:11:21,220
Stop it.

222
00:11:21,480 --> 00:11:22,600
She's just pregnant.

223
00:11:22,600 --> 00:11:23,570
It's still a delicate time.

224
00:11:23,570 --> 00:11:24,770
You mustn't hold her.

225
00:11:26,720 --> 00:11:27,120
Hello.

226
00:11:27,510 --> 00:11:28,650
Looking for something?

227
00:11:28,650 --> 00:11:30,080
I'm from a publishing house.

228
00:11:30,080 --> 00:11:30,880
Is Mr. Mu here?

229
00:11:31,120 --> 00:11:31,650
Publishing house?

230
00:11:31,650 --> 00:11:32,850
Come in. He's inside.

231
00:11:33,750 --> 00:11:34,320
Mr. Peng,

232
00:11:35,510 --> 00:11:37,370
although I dabble in many fields,

233
00:11:37,790 --> 00:11:39,550
I really don't know

234
00:11:40,480 --> 00:11:41,750
what to write about.

235
00:11:42,440 --> 00:11:45,320
What direction do you think I should take?

236
00:11:46,910 --> 00:11:49,200
Song porcelain is quite popular lately.

237
00:11:49,320 --> 00:11:49,960
We could

238
00:11:49,960 --> 00:11:52,080
write something about that

239
00:11:52,320 --> 00:11:53,380
to test the waters.

240
00:11:53,550 --> 00:11:54,840
After all, we're self-publishing.

241
00:11:54,840 --> 00:11:56,600
We should consider the sales potential.

242
00:11:56,600 --> 00:11:57,790
Forget about it.

243
00:11:57,790 --> 00:11:59,320
Too many people are working on that.

244
00:11:59,320 --> 00:12:00,320
I've said it before,

245
00:12:00,320 --> 00:12:01,920
I'm not doing this for money.

246
00:12:03,150 --> 00:12:05,150
It's purely for sharing knowledge.

247
00:12:05,510 --> 00:12:06,480
What do you think

248
00:12:07,030 --> 00:12:08,110
about black pottery figurines?

249
00:12:08,110 --> 00:12:09,390
Black pottery figurines?

250
00:12:09,390 --> 00:12:10,320
That could work.

251
00:12:10,840 --> 00:12:12,550
I have a friend whose cousin

252
00:12:12,570 --> 00:12:13,830
works in archaeology.

253
00:12:14,360 --> 00:12:16,870
The black pottery figurines
passed through his hands back then.

254
00:12:16,870 --> 00:12:19,360
It caused quite a stir
when they were brought back to China.

255
00:12:19,360 --> 00:12:21,820
No one here had seen
anything like it before.

256
00:12:21,850 --> 00:12:23,240
Where did he do his archaeological work?

257
00:12:23,240 --> 00:12:24,100
In Yin Village.

258
00:12:24,270 --> 00:12:24,870
I heard

259
00:12:25,200 --> 00:12:27,200
they discovered a large tomb there.

260
00:12:28,930 --> 00:12:31,320
I have some knowledge
about black pottery figurines.

261
00:12:31,320 --> 00:12:32,720
I'll write about it then.

262
00:12:34,550 --> 00:12:35,200
Director Zhang,

263
00:12:35,200 --> 00:12:37,320
isn't the scenery here
in Yin Village beautiful?

264
00:12:37,320 --> 00:12:38,150
Of course.

265
00:12:38,660 --> 00:12:39,520
If it weren't,

266
00:12:39,550 --> 00:12:41,350
why would nobles be buried here?

267
00:12:42,030 --> 00:12:43,090
The ancients said,

268
00:12:43,440 --> 00:12:46,000
"Serve the dead as you
would serve the living."

269
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:48,270
Even in death, they wanted a scenic view.

270
00:12:49,320 --> 00:12:50,000
Director Zhang,

271
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:51,030
so who do you think

272
00:12:51,030 --> 00:12:52,790
could be buried down there?

273
00:12:56,440 --> 00:12:58,500
Well, that depends on what you dig up.

274
00:12:58,700 --> 00:13:00,560
Isn't that why you called me here?

275
00:13:02,790 --> 00:13:05,050
I've been waiting for you two to speak up.

276
00:13:05,650 --> 00:13:07,080
This tomb must be big.

277
00:13:08,960 --> 00:13:09,420
Come on.

278
00:13:11,960 --> 00:13:12,320
Here.

279
00:13:13,630 --> 00:13:14,000
Look.

280
00:13:17,320 --> 00:13:18,910
Based on recent surveys,

281
00:13:19,250 --> 00:13:20,750
we've concluded that

282
00:13:21,270 --> 00:13:23,320
this tomb faces east

283
00:13:23,600 --> 00:13:25,130
with four burial passages:

284
00:13:25,240 --> 00:13:27,240
North passage: 36.5 meters long,

285
00:13:27,790 --> 00:13:29,910
7.8–31.3 meters wide;

286
00:13:30,480 --> 00:13:32,840
South passage: 32.7 meters long,

287
00:13:33,030 --> 00:13:35,080
9.7–40.2 meters wide;

